Section E. Preparation of Records of Trial (ROT)

E.1. Audio recording All special and general courts-martial proceedings must be recorded. See RCM 1112(a). 
required The preferred method for recording trial proceedings is by a mu lti-channel redundant 
digital recording device operated by a qua lified Coast Guard court reporter, civilian 
contractor court-reporter, or qualified court-reporter from another armed service. Do not 
use any other method without prior authori zation from the Office of Military Justice 
(CG-LMJ).

E.2. Sealed recordings Those portions of the recorded trial proceedings that are required to be sealed must be 
separated. See Subsection 21.E.7.a.

E.3. Contents of ROT The ROT in each general and special court-martial must contain the following materials, 
in the following order:

a. Cover and chronology sheets;

b. The STR;

c. Any action by the convening authority under RCM 1109 or 1110;

d. The judgment entered into the record by the military judge;

e. A digital audio file of the substantially verbatim recording of the court-martial;

f. If necessary, a digital audio file of sealed proceedings;

g. If necessary, an annotation with a time stamp of the sealed audio proceedings;

h. The charge sheet;

i. The convening order and any amendments, in order from oldest to most recent;

j. The request, if any, for trial by military judge alone;

k. The accused’s election, if any, of members under RCM 903, and, when 
applicable, any statement by the convening authority required under RCM 
503(a)(2);

l. The accused’s election, if any for se ntencing under the post-January 1, 2019 
sentencing rules under RCM 902A;

m. The accused’s election, if any, for sentencing by members in lieu of sentencing 
by a military judge under RCM 1002(b);

n. All prosecution exhibits;

o. All defense exhibits; and

p. All appellate exhibits.

E.4. Certification

E.4.a. Certification by the Within five days of entry of judgment into the record or receipt of the certified verbatim 
Court Reporter  transcript per Subsection 21.E.5. (whichever is later), the court reporter must certify that 
the ROT includes all of the items described in 21.E.3, using the template certificate 
found on the Office of Military Justice (CG-LMJ) website, 
https://uscg.uscg.afpims.mil/Resources/Legal/Military-Justice/. The court reporter, in 
coordination with the trial co unsel, is ultimately responsible for the accuracy and 
completeness of the ROT. Once the ROT has been certified for completeness and 
accuracy, the court reporter will then send electronically the certified ROT with certified 
transcript to the military judge.

